Goal: Understand what a thread actually is

+ What is a Thread (really)?
    A thread is a path of execution inside a process.
    Process â†’ JVM running
    Thread â†’ independent execution flow inside that JVM
    All threads share heap memory
    Each thread has its own stack
    So when you start multiple threads, the CPU scheduler decides who runs when.

 + Thread vs Runnable (core distinction)

    Thread
    Represents both the task and the execution
    You extend Thread and override run()

    Runnable
    Represents only the task
    Execution is handled by a Thread

+ Prefer Runnable (separates what to do from how to run)
    NEW
    â†“ start()
    RUNNABLE â†â”€ scheduler picks
    â†“
    RUNNING
    â†“
    WAITING / TIMED_WAITING (sleep, join, wait)
    â†“
    TERMINATED

    Key points:
    start() â†’ creates a new call stack
    run() called directly âŒ â†’ runs like a normal method (NO new thread)

+ sleep() vs join() (very important)

    sleep(ms)
    Pauses current thread
    Does not release locks
    Does not coordinate threads


    join()
    One thread waits for another thread to finish
    Used for coordination
    worker.join(); // main waits

    ğŸ‘‰ sleep â‰  synchronization
    Sleep just delays â€” it doesnâ€™t guarantee order.

+ Thread names & priorities
    Thread name
    Helps with debugging & logs.

    Thread t = new Thread(task, "Worker-1");

    Priority
    Hint to scheduler (NOT guaranteed)
    t.setPriority(Thread.MAX_PRIORITY); // 10

    âš ï¸ Priority is platform dependent. Never rely on it for correctness.

âœ” Threads run independently
âœ” Order is not deterministic
âœ” sleep() delays, join() coordinates
âœ” Thread names matter for debugging
âœ” Priority is a hint, not a rule